% ===========================================================================
% urcu-txn.bib -- shared bibliography for the urcu-txn paper series.
%
% Referenced by every paper in this repository as \bibliography{../common/urcu-txn}
% (make arxiv rewrites the path to \bibliography{urcu-txn} when flattening the
% submission tree). Style: natbib + bibtex, plainnat.
%
% VERIFICATION POLICY
% -------------------
% Every entry below was checked against a primary or authoritative source
% before being added. Entries whose BibTeX was exported from DBLP carry a
% "verified:" comment naming the DBLP record. Entries not in DBLP (theses,
% technical reports, web documents) carry a comment naming the source that
% was actually fetched and read. Nothing here is reconstructed from memory.
%
% UNVERIFIED ENTRIES: none.
%
% Two entries are worth calling out as *not* DBLP-backed, though both were
% verified against primary sources:
%   - mckenney1998rcu   : PDCS'98 is not indexed by DBLP. Title, authors and
%                         author order were read off the authors' own proof PDF;
%                         the page range (509--518) was taken from the reference
%                         list of desnoyers2012urcu, which cites it directly.
%   - baskins2002judy / silverstein2002judymanual : Judy was never published as
%                         a paper. Both documents were fetched and read.
%
% CONVENTIONS
% -----------
%   - Keys are <firstauthor><year><shorttopic>, all lowercase.
%   - DOIs are recorded lowercase, matching the resolver URL.
%   - Sections below mirror the areas the series draws on.
%   - The PATENTS / PRIOR ART section at the end of this file records granted
%     U.S. patents rather than literature. Each entry carries its filing and
%     grant dates, assignee, term-expiration date and legal status as read off
%     the public record, plus a plain-language summary of claim 1. Status
%     fields are point-in-time observations, not legal conclusions -- see the
%     section preamble for the caveats that apply to them.
%   - Never put a bare at-sign in a comment -- not in an email address, and not
%     when naming an entry type in prose. BibTeX scans for the at-sign even
%     inside comment lines and tries to parse what follows as an entry type,
%     emitting "immediately follows an entry type" errors and skipping input.
%     Write email addresses as "user at host", and name entry types without the
%     sigil ("a misc entry"). This matters more than it looks: paper.mk runs
%     bibtex with a leading '-', so such errors do NOT fail the build -- they
%     can silently drop entries. Keep this file bibtex-clean; a run over this
%     file must report zero error messages.
% ===========================================================================


