% --- Family: generation number / consistent cyclic search ---

% CLAIM 1 (method). An updater publishes a new version of a group data element
% without locks or atomic instructions, as follows: create the new element;
% stamp it with a new generation number distinct from the group's global
% generation number; link the new element to its prior version and the prior
% version back to it (a two-way version link); splice the new element into the
% group so readers can reach it; then update the group's single global
% generation number to the new value; free the prior version and its version
% links after a grace period. A reader stamps its search with the current
% global generation number and, on reaching an element whose generation number
% differs, walks the version links to the version matching its own stamp.
% Relevance: the global generation number is a single shared word whose update
% is what makes the new versions current for subsequent readers -- the nearest
% pre-2015 McKenney analogue of a flip-latch. It differs from a status-word
% flip in that readers do not test a boolean existence bit; they compare
% generation numbers and traverse version links to reach a correct version, so
% old and new versions coexist and are both reachable.
